50|$|The {{snow pea}} (Pisum sativum var. saccharatum) is a vegetable, more {{specifically}} {{a variety of}} pea eaten whole in its pod while still unripe. The name <b>mangetout</b> (French for “eat all”) can apply both to snow peas and to snap peas.|$|E
50|$|Peach v Tesco Stores Plc 1998 C.L.Y. 1665, Mrs Peach, 65, {{slipped on}} a <b>mangetout</b> (a pea pod) {{in the store}} and hurt her hip, requirng surgery. She had {{recovered}} after 3 months but developed deep vein thrombosis. She got £10,000 in compensation.|$|E
5000|$|Snap peas (Pisum sativum var. macrocarpon), {{also known}} as sugar snap peas, are a {{cultivar}} group of edible-podded peas that differ from snow peas in that their pods are round as opposed to flat. The name <b>mangetout</b> (French for [...] "eat all") can apply both to snap peas and snow peas.|$|E
